Department: HEALTH INFORMATION MANAGEMENT

HISTORY AND PHYSICAL February 8, 2011 8:19am
Dictated By: ERIC A POULIN MD
Signed By: ERIC A POULIN MD
Name: SSATEST,KANABEC Acct #: H0008805
Date of birth:06/02/1968 MR#: M000382
Report Status: Signed
Date: 02/06/11
Dictating Provider: ERIC A POULIN MD
CHIEF COMPLAINT: Testing second stay.
HISTORY OF PRESENT ILLNESS: See previous history and physical. Patient was
discharged just over 24 hours ago and returns with recurrent abdominal pain.
PAST MEDICAL HISTORY: Status post appendectomy 4 days ago.
MEDICATIONS: Antibiotics, aspirin once daily.
ALLERGIES: No known drug allergies
HABITS: Non smoker. Drinks alcohol occasionally.
FAMILY HISTORY: Mother alive and well. Father died of an MI in his 60s.
SOCIAL HISTORY: Married with children.
REVIEW OF SYSTEMS: No fever. No chills. Recurrent abdominal pain after
surgery. All other review of systems negative or normal.
PHYSICAL EXAMINATION
VITAL SIGNS: Temperature 97.8, vital signs stable.
GENERAL: Ill-appearing patient.
HEENT: Normocephalic. Atraumatic.
NECK: Supple.
LUNGS: Clear to auscultation bilaterally.
CARDIAC: Regular rate and rhythm. No murmurs, rubs or gallops.
ABDOMEN: Soft, tenderness generalized to lower quadrants.
EXTREMITIES: No edema.
NEUROLOGICAL: Cranial nerves II-XII are intact.
DIAGNOSTIC DATA: Pending. Abdominal x-ray was normal.
ASSESSMENT: Recurrent abdominal pain post appendectomy 4 days ago with no fever
or chills.
PLAN: Keep patient overnight and get pain under control while we wait for labs
to return.
POULIN,ERIC A MD
02/09/11 1531

Department: HEALTH INFORMATION MANAGEMENT
Report #1:
SURGICAL REPORT February 2, 2011 9:13am
Dictated By: JANICE L FLEMING MD
Signed By: JANICE L FLEMING MD
Name: SSATEST,KANABEC Acct #: H0008615
Date of birth:06/02/1968 MR#: M000382
Report Status: Signed
Date of Service: 02/02/11
Surgeon: JANICE L FLEMING MD
Referring Provider: ERIC A POULIN, MD
PREOPERATIVE DIAGNOSIS: Abdominal pain.
POSTOPERATIVE DIAGNOSIS: Abdominal pain
PROCEDURE PERFORMED: Colonoscopy.
HISTORY: Patient was admitted with abdominal pain.
PHYSICAL EXAMINATION: Chest and heart within normal limits.
PROCEDURE: After prep of Mag citrate and GoLYTELY heparin lock was put in
place. Patient was given 2.5 mg of Versed and 2 cc of Sublimaze IV during the
course of examination. Patient was then placed in the left lateral position. On
rectal exam no masses are felt. The Olympus PCF-H180AL video endoscope was
introduced without difficulty and advanced into the cecum. Appendiceal orifice
is unremarkable as is the ileocecal valve. Mucosa of the cecum, ascending,
transverse, descending and sigmoid are unremarkable. On retroflexion of the
scope in the rectum some small external hemorrhoids are seen. The endoscope is
then withdrawn and the patient released to go home after a period of observation
in the endoscopy suite.
IMPRESSION: No colonoscopic findings to explain abdominal pain.
PLAN: Patient will need to be followed by general surgery.
FLEMING,JANICE L MD
02/08/11 0942

Report #2:
SURGICAL REPORT February 2, 2011 9:14am
Dictated By: JANICE L FLEMING MD
Signed By: JANICE L FLEMING MD
Name: SSATEST,KANABEC Acct #: H0008615
Date of birth:06/02/1968 MR#: M000382
Report Status: Signed
Date of Service: 02/02/11
Surgeon: JANICE L FLEMING MD
Referring Provider: ERIC A POULIN, MD
PREOPERATIVE DIAGNOSIS: Abdominal pain.
POSTOPERATIVE DIAGNOSIS: Abdominal pain.
PROCEDURE PERFORMED: Upper GI endoscopy.
HISTORY: Patient was admitted with abdominal pain.
PHYSICAL EXAM: Chest and heart within normal limits.
PROCEDURE: After placement of heparin lock patient was given 2 cc of Sublimaze
and 3.5 mg of Versed IV to titrate the patient to conscious sedation. The GIF-
Q160 video endoscope was then introduced without difficulty. On examination of
the esophagus mucosa is unremarkable. There is no inflammation seen at the GE
junction. On entry into the stomach there is a large amount of bile in the
stomach with bile staining particularly in the antrum. On retroflexion of the
scope no significant hiatal hernia is seen. The pylorus is opened, endoscope
advanced into the duodenum. First, second and third portions were examined and
no lesions were seen. Unable to visualize the ampullae. The endoscope was then
withdrawn and the patient released to go home after period of observation in the
endoscopy suite.
IMPRESSION: No upper GI findings to suggest abdominal pain.
PLAN: Patient to be followed by general surgery.
FLEMING,JANICE L MD
02/09/11 1531

Report #3:
SURGICAL REPORT February 2, 2011 9:29am
Dictated By: VICTOR S LIEW MBBS
Signed By: VICTOR S LIEW MBBS
Name: SSATEST,KANABEC Acct #: H0008615
Date of birth:06/02/1968 MR#: M000382
Report Status: Signed
Date of Service: 02/02/11
Surgeon: VICTOR S LIEW MBBS
Referring Provider: ERIC A POULIN, MD
PREOPERATIVE DIAGNOSIS: Acute appendicitis.
POSTOPERATIVE DIAGNOSIS: Acute appendicitis.
PROCEDURE PERFORMED: Laparoscopic appendectomy.
ESTIMATED BLOOD LOSS: Minimal.
SPECIMENS SENT: Appendix.
DRAINS: None.
COMPLICATIONS: None.
FINDINGS: Acutely inflamed appendix.
INDICATIONS: Patient was seen in consultation earlier by Dr. Oakes with
undefinitive diagnosis at that time. Patient had colonoscopy and upper GI which
both were negative for findings in relation to abdominal pain. X-rays and CT are
back showing acute appendicitis.
OPERATIVE NOTE: The patient was brought to the operating room, placed on the
table in a supine position. After adequate anesthesia had been administered the
patient's identity and the procedure to be performed was confirmed and agreed
upon by the surgical team. Prior to surgery SED's had been applied to the
patient and antibiotics had been administered as well prior to the incision.
The patient's abdomen was the prepped and draped in the standard fashion with
ChloraPrep and sterile towels. Approximately 20 cc of 0.25% Marcaine with
epinephrine was used for local anesthetic effect throughout the entire case at
the skin incision sites. A curvilinear incision was made just above the
umbilicus through an old scar site. Dissection was carried out down through the
subcutaneous plane, down through the abdominal wall fascia. This was entered
sharply and careful dissection further beyond this layer gained entrance into
the intraabdominal cavity. A 12 mm trocar was then placed down through this
incision site into the abdominal cavity. A 30* 5 mm scope was then passed down
through the trocar after the abdomen, then insufflated with carbon dioxide to 15
mmHg of pressure. Under direct vision a 5 mm trocar was placed through a small
incision in the lower abdomen in the midline. A grasper was then placed through
this trocar in order to help manipulate the bowel around the area of the right
lower quadrant. In doing so the cecum was identified and acutely inflamed
appendix could be seen coming off of the cecum. At this point a 5 mm trocar was
inserted in the right upper quadrant through a small skin incision under direct
vision with a laparoscope. The mesoappendix and the base of the appendix were
dissected out. A window was created at the base of the appendix between these
two structures. A linear cutting stapler was then placed through the 12 mm
trocar and clamped across the base of the appendix. This was then fired after
confirming that the tips of the stapler were free of any other tissue. Vascular
staples were then placed in the endoscopic stapler and two loads were fired
across the mesoappendix. This freed the appendix up entirely. An endobag was
then inserted through the 12 mm trocar and the appendix was placed within the
endobag. It was then brought out through the umbilical incision site. This was
sent for specimen. The 12 mm trocar was reinserted in the umbilical incision
site. Further inspection did not reveal any other significant pathology.
Irrigation was performed. A final look at the base of the appendix at the cecum
confirmed the staple lines to be intact and adequate hemostasis to be achieved.
The two 5 mm trocars were then removed under direct vision with the
laparoscope. The 12 m trocar was then removed. The abdomen was desufflated of
carbon dioxide. The supraumbilical incision was closed in two layers. The
fascial layer was closed using 0-Vicryl. All skin incisions were then closed
using 4-0 Monocryl in a subcuticular fashion. Steri-Strips and sterile
